Generally, the corresponding band gaps can be estimated according to the formula ahv = A(hv − E

                           g
                        )n, where a, h, v, Eg and A are absorption coefficient, Planck constant, light frequency, band gap and a constant, respectively. Among them, n is 2 for direct-gap semiconductor and 1/2 for indirect-gap semiconductor [4]. As can be seen in Fig. 5c, the band gap of MoO3−x and g-C3N4 is 2.44 and 2.87 eV, respectively, consistent with previous literature [19,44]. Furthermore, the potentials of VB and CB of a semiconductor are calculated using the relation: EVB = χ − Ee + 0.5Eg and ECB = EVB − Eg, where EVB and ECB are the valence band (VB) and conduction band (CB), χ is the electronegativity of the semiconductor, Ee is the energy of free electrons on the hydrogen scale (about 4.5 eV) [45–47]. According to the literature [19,20], after calculation by above formula, the VB potentials and CB potentials of g-C3N4 are 1.66 and −1.21 eV, respectively, and the VB potentials and CB potentials of MoO3−x are 2.78 and 0.34 eV, respectively.
